John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have traditionally provided excellent education. Looking at recent outstanding exam results, this situation has not changed until 2018, which is further reinforced by individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
In Scotland, more than 30,000 students are already enrolled in institutions of this kind, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), which strive to provide the best possible services to students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare students for further education, higher education, their chosen careers and their roles as citizens of the world.
In an educational sector where it is possible to design and implement customized school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to prove to be popular and sought-after subjects.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to someone in a language they understand, they get to their head.
But if you speak in his language, it goes to his heart.”
This is an important reminder, because we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s exam results show that students from independent schools across the country have produced the best results from foreign languages.
Of all students studying a foreign language, 68 per cent achieved a higher grade A (over 85 per cent).
According to the data collected from the 74 member schools of SCIS, 72 percent of students received a higher A grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students achieved a A grade.
These findings also show that independent schools in Scotland see foreign languages as essential knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Nowadays, languages, as chosen subjects, have become at least as important as natural sciences, technology, engineering, and mathematics in both independent and non-independent schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Vocational Training found that 17 percent of employers said they found it difficult to fill vacancies because of a lack of language skills.
We can see from this that language skills are becoming increasingly necessary for young people to have successful careers.
As knowledge of foreign languages is expected in an increasing number of workplaces, language skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have studied a foreign language, you will gain a life-long knowledge that will bring you clear benefits.
Being able to communicate directly with people of other nationalities automatically gives a competitive advantage to applicants who speak more than one language.
According to a survey by YouGov, which surveyed 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents did not speak a foreign language well enough to communicate with others, and French was the only language spoken by more than 10 percent (15 percent).
Therefore, it is important to place emphasis on language teaching for children right now.
Speaking more languages, especially in developing countries, can be a tool for children to be equipped to apply for more important jobs as adults.
Every school in Scotland will be dealing with different languages.
Many schools will focus on classical modern languages, while more will teach languages such as Mandarin or Japanese that are expected to be of paramount importance for the UK by 2020.
Whatever your child’s area of interest, they will be able to learn multiple elective languages at independent schools and will be trained by educators who are experts in their field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment for children that prepares and equips them with the skills they will need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
It is not difficult to realize that in today’s global business environment, languages remain vital for the future of a country, and education must reflect this.
In fact, knowledge of modern languages should rather be treated as a "international communication skill".
Independent schools offer a choice, diverse and quality education for young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire – this is how it should be.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
