Harvard students are taught to take enough rest.
A new subject at Harvard University this year has prompted students to sleep more, fighting the growing macho culture of caffeinated whole-night learning.
One academic concluded that students at the world’s number one university are often completely lost when it comes to how they should care for themselves.
The course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the U.S., was designed by Professor Charles Czeisler, who teaches sleep medicine at Harvard College of Medicine and practicing as a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital.
He was inspired by the fact that he had previously given a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and asked, ‘Why do I have to face this now, as a senior?’
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told the Telegraph.
The course, launched for the first time this year, introduces students to the fundamental impact of good sleep habits on their academic and athletic performance, in addition to having a positive impact on their overall well-being.
According to Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of the University’s Health Service, the university decided to start the course because the students were found to be extremely sleepless during the week.
The one-hour course also includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one, for example, they show a picture of a dormitory room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and why bedtime routines matter.
In another section, participants are shown how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
They present a map of the campus area with interactive icons to encourage participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that we will not immediately change the behavior of our students.
But we think they have a right to this knowledge – just as they have a right to be aware of the health effects of smoking,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of learning through the night continues to flourish, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students are causing growing problems with sleep deprivation.
Sufficient and quality sleep is the student’s “secret weapon” in combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even obesity, as sleep deprivation forces the brain into a starving mode and causes a constant sense of hunger.
Raymond So helped Professor Czeisler design the course, a 19-year-old Californian student studying chemistry and biophysics, and last year he took a first-time course at Harvard.
He said that what he heard there had opened his eyes and encouraged him to advocate for a university-level education.
He hopes that as a next step, postgraduate students will also be able to participate in a similar training program before they find employment in the competitive sector.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set up a bedtime alert, a wake-up call, and familiarize themselves with the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electrical screens and LED light sources, which can easily deflect them from their daily rhythm and make it difficult to fall asleep.
