New Cancer Vaccine Could Teach Your Immune System to “See” Abnormal Cells
New Cancer Vaccine Could Teach Your Immune System to “See” and Destroy Abnormal Cells
A vaccine given as part of a treatment teaches the immune system to recognise abnormal cells.
Part of the method is to extract the immune cells from the patient and then modify them in a laboratory.
In this way, they are able to "see" the protein that accompanies many types of cancer. The treated immune cells are injected back into the patient.
An experimental vaccine achieved promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who was treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize abnormal cells could say goodbye to her ovarian cancer for more than 18 months.
The method involves extracting immune cells from the patient; modifying them in the laboratory to “see” a protein called HER2, which is a common accompaniment to multiple cancers; and then replanting the cells.
Jay Berzofsky, a professor at the American National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our findings suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "stimulates the growth of multiple cancers," including breast, ovarian, lung and rectum cancers, explains Professor Berzofsky.
A similar method, based on highlighting immune cells and “teaching” them how to attack cancer cells, has previously been successfully used in the treatment of one type of leukemia.
