What is the Global Citizens Festival and have you managed to reduce poverty?
On Saturday, New York City will host the annual music event Global Citizens Festival, where stars from around the world will take part in a truly noble effort to eradicate poverty globally.
The Global Citizens Festival will be held for the seventh time, with tens of thousands expected to fill the Great Grass of Central Park, where participants will not only be able to enjoy the performance of Janet Jackson, Cardi B or Shawn Mendes, but will also be able to draw attention to the true purpose of the event: to eradicate extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizens Festival was first held in 2012 as part of the Global Poverty Project, run by an international advocacy group that aims to eradicate poverty by engaging more and more people in the active fight against poverty.
The concert is free of charge for those (unless they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket) who undertake certain tasks or “actions”, such as volunteering, sending an e-mail to a senior politician, a phone call, or any other meaningful activity to draw attention to the purpose of the project: the eradication of poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen really been in achieving its goals over the past 12 years?
Is it really an effective way to reward people with a concert ticket to convince others about the importance of action, or is it just another form of so-called “clicktivism” when people feel they have made a meaningful contribution to a cause by signing an online petition or writing a Twitter post?
Since 2011, according to Global Citizen data, more than 19 million “actions” have been carried out by the project’s supporters, serving a variety of different purposes.
According to the organization, these actions have helped world leaders allocate <0x24>37 billion to policies and commitments to combat poverty that could impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group claimed 390 commitments and announcements to come from their actions, of which <0x24>10 billion have already been paid or collected through fundraising.
The group estimates that the money collected has directly affected the lives of nearly 649 million people.
Key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based partnership between investors and contractors that aims to “help children reach their full potential”. The organization has pledged <0x24>35 million to help Rwanda eradicate hunger after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from “global citizens”.
“With the support of the UK government and donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can banish social injustice and malnutrition into the footnotes of history books,” Tracey Ullman, the Power of Nutrition ambassador, told the crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also claims that after asking the UK in more than 5,000 actions to improve the nutrition of mothers and their children, the government has allocated funds for the Power of Nutrition project, which will improve the nutrition of 5 million women and children.
One of the frequently asked questions on the Global Citizen’s website is, “Why do you think extreme poverty can be eradicated?”
The Global Citizen responded: “It will be a long and difficult journey, one in which we sometimes get stuck and sometimes fail.
But like previous civil rights and anti-segregation movements, we will achieve our goal because together we are stronger.”
