The inventor of the World Wide Web would launch a new Internet to confront Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lee’s open source platform Solid.
With Solid, users can choose where they want to store their data and who can access the information.
In an exclusive interview with the Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt was to “take control of the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said about the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “personal online data warehouse”, also known as POD.
This can include lists, to-do lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
This is like having access to Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify from the same browser at the same time.
The unique thing about the personal online data warehouse is that the user can decide who has access to his or her data.
The company calls this “the realization of the individual’s right to self-determination over data”.
According to John Bruce, CEO of Inrupt, the company’s mission is to provide the resources, processes, and skills needed to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some contract developers working on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt.
Berners-Lee said he and his team weren’t asking Facebook and Google “whether to introduce a technology that would completely turn their business models upside down overnight.”
“We don’t ask for permission.”
In a post published on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s “mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that will help protect the integrity and quality of Solidra’s newly built network.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet by founding the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts University of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an important voice in the debate on internet neutrality.
Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute despite the launch of Inrupt.
“I am endlessly optimistic about the next era of the Internet,” Berners-Lee said.
Bernard Vann, a Victorian-Crusader pastor in World War I
The only Anglican pastor to receive the Victorian Cross celebrates in his hometown 100 years after his heroic deed in World War I.
Reverend Bernard Vann and Colonel-in-Chief earned the award during the September 29, 1918 attacks in Bellenglise and Lehacourt.
Four days later, however, he was killed by a sniper, so he never knew he had earned the highest award from the British Armed Forces.
The memorial was unveiled by two grandchildren at a Saturday ceremony in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandsons, Michael Vann, said it was “symbolic” that the memorial stone was handed over exactly 100 years after his grandfather’s meritorious act.
According to the London Gazette, Reverend Bernard Vann and Lieutenant Colonel led his battalion through the Canal de Saint-Quentin on September 29, 1918, "in the midst of thick fog and fierce cannon and machine gun fire."
Later, he hurried to the front line and, with "extraordinary heroism," took the lead of the battalion, then attacked a camp cannon detachment on his own, destroying three of its members.
Reverend Bernard Vann and lieutenant colonel were shot by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
“I know I’ll never get back to what my grandfather did, and that taught me humility,” said Michael Vann, 72.
After the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band, Michael Vann and his brother, Dr. James Vann, wreathed the memorial stone.
Michael Vann said he felt honored to play a part in the ceremony and added: “The courage of a true hero is demonstrated by the number of people who later pay him tribute.”
