Germany's newest warship has been postponed
The German navy’s latest frigate was supposed to be in service in 2014 to replace the ageing Cold War warships, but due to various system failures and exponentially rising costs, this is expected to happen at least until next year.
The inauguration of the flagship of the brand new Baden-Württemberg-class frigates, “Rheinland-Pfalz”, has been postponed to the first half of 2019, the weekly Die Zeit wrote, citing an army spokesman.
The ship was initially scheduled to join the Navy in 2014, but the ongoing delays made the fate of the large-scale project very difficult.
In 2007, the Navy ordered four Baden-Württemberg-class ships to replace the Bremen-class ageing frigates.
It will be equipped with various anti-aircraft missiles and camouflage technology, including a signal damper that reduces the ship’s radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Another important feature is that it requires less maintenance, which in practice means that these new frigates can be put into service for up to two years away from the mother ports.
However, because of the project’s continuous delay, these high-tech warships, which Germany could use to feel its power overseas, may become obsolete by the time they are finally put into service, Die Zeit noted.
The fateful F125 frigate hit the headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to inaugurate it and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had sent a ship back to the manufacturer.
Not much has been revealed about the reasons for the return, but the German media has cited several critical "software and hardware bugs" that make the warship unusable on a combat mission.
Software shortages are a major problem, as the Baden-Württemberg-class warships will have only 120 sailors, which is only half the crew of the old Bremen-class frigates.
It has also been found that the ship is extremely overweight, which impairs its performance and makes it impossible for the Navy to make further adjustments later on.
The 7,000-ton Rhineland-Palatinate is said to be twice as heavy as the similar class of ships the Germans put into service during World War II.
Apart from the faulty parts, the increase in the total cost of the project, including the training of the crew, is a growing problem.
