According to the official, the problem has in the meantime become a self-exciting process, as the old ships had to be dismantled, but there are no more ships to replace the fallout.
He expressed concern that none of the Baden-Württemberg-class frigates were able to join the navy.
The National Trust is investigating the secret life of bats.
New research is underway on a Scottish Highland estate to find out how bats exploit the features of the landscape while hunting.
The researchers hope that the results will provide new information on the behaviour of single flying mammals, which could also be useful for future conservation initiatives.
Scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will study the behavior of common and soprano bats, as well as brown long-eared bats and water bats in the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at the appropriate points in the area to record bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will use handheld detectors to collect mobile data.
A detailed analysis of the recordings’ sound material can be used to determine the frequency of bat sounds and what species are doing.
The researchers also produce a habitat map and a report, which can be used to determine in detail how the behavior of the animals develops depending on the landscape.
NTS conservation advisor Rob Dewar hopes the results will reveal the most important habitats for bats and how they are used.
This information will help to determine the beneficial effects of habitat management work, such as meadows, and how best to preserve forested areas for bats and other affected species.
The size of the bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined significantly over the last century.
Construction and land development work disrupts the animals’ sleeping areas and reduces their living space.
Wind turbines and public lighting are also a risk factor for them, as are exposed fly papers, certain chemical processes used in building materials, and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not completely blind.
But because they are night predators, they rely more on their hearing when they hunt prey than on their sight.
With their sophisticated technique based on ultrasound reflection, they can determine the exact location of insects and the objects in their path.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 acres of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
They work with ten trained professionals who regularly conduct studies and sleep-place tests, and occasionally participate in rescue work.
The organization created Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
According to property manager David Thompson, the area is an ideal habitat for bats.
"There's a great place for bats in Threave," he said.
“There are old buildings, lots of old trees, and everything else you need for a good living space.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats yet, and the work we’ve done here and in other areas like this will help us learn more about what they need to feel good about themselves.”
He also underlined the importance of making sure that there are bats living there before renovating buildings, as the destruction of a single site could result in the death of 400 females and juveniles, leading to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected animals, and their destruction, harassment and habitat disturbance are prohibited by law.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish representative of the Bat Conservation Trust, also called on the public to help.
"There is still a lot we don't know about bats, and we have almost no information about the population status of most domestic species."
